      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Age Is Now</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Francis W Rodgers letter responds to July 2 comment on what to call people who used to be 'old'</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What to Call People Who Used to Be Old,'' by Dudley Clendinen (Editorial Observer, July 2):</p>
        <p>Mr. Clendinen, who comments on ''recrafting the language of longevity,'' raises a nonexistent issue. Whether you are a teenager, or 67, like me, or one of those 90-year-olds mentioned in the article, the issue is ''now.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What to Call People Who Used to Be Old,'' by Dudley Clendinen (Editorial Observer, July 2):</p>
        <p>Mr. Clendinen, who comments on ''recrafting the language of longevity,'' raises a nonexistent issue. Whether you are a teenager, or 67, like me, or one of those 90-year-olds mentioned in the article, the issue is ''now.''</p>
        <p>It is life among the living. Life and death are random, kind or cruel. The mystery remains. A new name for ''now'' adds nothing.</p>
        <p>FRANCIS W. RODGERS  Rensselaer, N.Y., July 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
